<hr />

<p>The reference directory contains structural doctrine, subsystem nodes, and navigation aids that pretend this is an information architecture instead of a graveyard. This layer is where the archive explains how it thinks it works. Everything else is where it proves otherwise.</p>

<p>Reference docs fall into two species: <strong>Doctrine Sheets</strong> (MAP, SAC, SSP — attempts to codify behavior into categories) and <strong>Reference Nodes</strong> (overviews like BHDSS or Synthetic Affect &amp; Successor Suite that summarize incident clusters in plain language).</p>

<p>Cross-links point down into Lorelog, mascots, posts, haiku, and limericks. Nothing in reference is allowed to exist without at least one dependent ghost.</p>

<h2>Known Doctrine Clusters</h2>

<ul>
  <li><strong>Managed Absence Spine (CAAR/LCGU/STCP/AAOA)</strong> — A containment structure for procedural disappearance patterns across forms and archival null states.</li>
  <li><strong>Synthetic Affect Successor Suite (SCAS/FSD/AH-1/PRE/SSP)</strong> — A layered affect simulation framework tracking post-human emotional continuity experiments and their derivative systems.</li>
  <li><strong>LBP-01 (Lorelog Backfeed Protocol)</strong> — The meta-governance mechanism that routes interpretive residue from Lorelog entries back into structural doctrine for reclassification and drift correction.</li>
</ul>

<p>If you are about to add a new cluster of weirdness: file the incidents first, then add a reference node here that admits what you just did.</p>

